snippet.textDisplay:
In fairness to Singularity, pretty much every single thing that went wrong in this build was either Linus' or Alex's fault (but mostly Linus), as the manufacturer seems to have thought of everything, and tried to make this as easy as it can be.
Sure, the manual wasnt great, but lets be honest: Which water cooling enthusiast DOES NOT know about water pumps and O-rings?

Linus managed to get pretty much everything wrong, and the main reason for these screw-ups was that there was little to no planning ahead and thinking. They just went "Ok, seems easy, lets do this", and just did things without thinking very much.

Terrible, just terrible.

As for the case, while I can see some of its appeal, it doesnt provide the best and easiest water cooling installation experience.
The main reason for this is that its a little small, and you want the biggest case you can find, when doing a custom water cooling rig.
Besides that, while the fact that its got a built-in reservoir and a dedicated spot for a water pump might seem nice, its actually more limiting in terms of what you can do, since the holes and fittings for them are fixed, which means you have to plan with those specific spots and measurements in mind.

Ideally, custom water cooling builders want to do their own thing, and have the freedom to build the thing exactly as they like it.
The pre-installed built-in stuff just limits you more, and it might even make things harder, since you might need new fittings, tubes, etc, so in the end it ends up being more of a headache than an advantage.
